recordings.rmk:
Traills flycatcher seen well by two birders with binoculars. Photographed. Identified as Alder after hearing repeated "pip" calls at fairly close range.

Pitch of repeated calls varies only very slightly, toward end of clip.

Weather sunny, warm and breezy as the tail end of a weak "cold" front passed through.

- No edits or other modification to recording (beyond addition of fade-in, fade-out)

- Traills flycatcher foraging above overgrown trail at mid-story in trees along north end of Cones Dike (peninsular dike through flooded Paynes Prairie)

- Tail-flicking, frequent sallies typical of active foraging

- no unusual plumage recognized

- sex unknown

See additional remarks and photos on ebird checklist of 9 October 2021:
https://ebird.org/checklist/S95864655

recordings.rmk: I was walking a nature trail over Togus Stream behind the Togus VA Medical Center, through field and marsh and woods.  I heard what I thought might be an Alder Flycatcher and played a recording for it.  Shortly this bird flew into a birch tree and called.  I wasn't sure if it was an alder when I compared it to the recording of willow flycatcher.  The recording level is low but seems clear to me.  It has not been altered. I hope you can identify the other birds calling around it, too.  It was a very warm day for Maine, sunny and little wind.

First individual singing from different trees at close range and second inconspicuous individual calling farther away. Habitat: stunted coniferous forest, clearcut, mature coniferous forest.

Singing from trees adjacent to ponds. There is an interesting double-vocalization at 1:20.5, where either the bird stutters or a second individual sings nearby. Perhaps it is a Willow Flycatcher? Also, Willow Flycatcher at 0:05?

## Conditions

 Clear sky, about 60°F,  warming from an overnight freeze.

## Equipment

Recorded on a Sennheiser MKE 400 microphone with a wind baffle into a Panasonic GH2 camera at 192 kbps.

## Modifications

 Trimmed stretches without songs from front  and back. Amplified to peak at –3.0 dB.

Recorded on iPhone 5 using EIM-001 microphone and RODE Rec app. Imported to Audacity with minor trim to shorten the gaps and eliminate "dead air". High Pass Filter to 2400Hz with a rolloff of 24dB to eliminate the nearby foot traffic noise.

Marsh environment. Bird was in a bush beside the small side marsh at this location. Was sitting and would occasionally hunt. Otherwise rather stationary. 

Noted that this bird made its call during the pauses between other birds calling in the vicinity. Other bird sounds were edited out for the purpose of making this call be at the foreground. In the original there was a gap of about 5-7 seconds between each of these calls in which other birds were singing.

Brief altercation/chase beginning at end of 0:56 as birds fly over me, then male sang perched exposed (a bit odd for fall Alder) 30' away at 25' from near the top of a large prickly ash from 1:22 through remainder of recording. This was recorded on the west/central edge of the refuge along Red River. Immediate habitat- dry, sandy- small opening among extensive clumps of med/low Chickasaw plum- with roughleaf dogwood, peppervine, goatweed and scattered larger prickly ash. The bird continued singing perched obscured shortly after- with apparent same bird singing upon my return from farther north 15-20 minutes later. Exceptional numbers were noted this day of Alder Flycatcher, Blue-gray Gnatcatcher and Yellow-breasted Chat still either lingering or passing through- among lower numbers of other migrants.

Two birds countering. Taking into consideration that many Willow Flycatcher calls can be similar, it was also used for playback (often first) during many of the surveys of 2013-14. Although WIFL is not a super rare migrant here, interestingly, there was zero response during either year.

recordings.rmk: Recorded using my Motorola Razr M and Tape-A-Talk.

This bird was one of 3 ALFL seen and heard at this location on this date. It was calling the flat "pip" note repeatedly. The bird was photographed. This species is rare in central Florida. The location is within the Payne's Prairie Preserve State Park. This individual was inhabiting a thicket of Rubus and Persimmons. This recording was made using the voice recorder app on my iphone. I amplified it slightly using Audacity software but no other edits were made.
